<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900921-0067</DOCNO><DOCID>900921-0067.</DOCID><HL>   REC, Others Settle   SEC Fraud Charges   On Stock Purchases</HL><DATE>09/21/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C10</SO><IN>SECURITIES (SCR)BANKS (BNK)</IN><GV>SECURITIES AND EXCHANGE COMMISSION (SEC)</GV><LP>   WASHINGTON -- The Securities and Exchange Commissionaccused REC Investors Inc. of buying about $150 million ofsecurities without having enough money to pay for them.   The complaint also named the firm's sole shareholder,Robert E. Connors, and National State Bank of Summit, N.J.The bank was accused of lending the firm money to buy thestock with insufficient collateral.</LP><TEXT>   According to the commission, REC, based in Far Hills,N.J., purchased about $150 million of securities withoutsufficient funds to pay for the trades in 1987 and 1988. Itearned $2.6 million in profit on the trades.   At the same time the suit was filed, the defendantssettled, without admitting any violations. Under the consentagreement, REC will disgorge $47,803, representing the coststhat the firm would have incurred, plus interest, had itborrowed the funds in compliance with margin rules, whichallow investors to buy stock without putting up the fullcost.   Mr. Connors and the bank agreed to refrain from thealleged violations in the future.   In a separate settlement of administrative proceedingsagainst REC and Mr. Connors, REC agreed to a censure from theagency and Mr. Connors agreed to a 15-day suspension oftrading.   Mr. Connors couldn't be reached for comment yesterday.</TEXT></DOC>